7.1.1 - W11SR16: Inadequate Email Classification and DLP Management
ISM controls:
•	0553; 1234 (Relating to the use of protective markings and email classification).
•	0607; 0608 (Relating to the implementation and monitoring of Data Loss Prevention (DLP) controls).
•	1148 (Relating to the filtering of incoming and outgoing email for malicious or unauthorised content).
•	1540 (Relating to the retention of logs for security and data spill investigations).
Current Risk
There is a risk that the inadequate management of email classification and Data Loss Prevention (DLP) systems within the Windows 11 and Microsoft 365 environment will lead to the accidental or malicious exposure and exfiltration of sensitive information. In the event of a data spill, a lack of robust classification and monitoring tools could result in significant agency reputational damage and legal non-compliance with government data protection standards.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
LIKELY	x	MAJOR	=	HIGH
Recommendations:
•	Deploy Mandatory Sensitivity Labelling: Implement Microsoft Information Protection (MIP) sensitivity labels that mandate users classify every email and document before it can be sent or saved.
•	Automate DLP Policies: Configure automated DLP rules in Microsoft Purview to detect and block the transmission of sensitive data (e.g., TFNs, medical records, or specific departmental keywords) to external or unauthorised recipients.
•	User Data Handling Education: Conduct regular, mandatory training for all staff on the correct application of protective markings and the importance of adhering to DLP policies for agency data.
- Treatment #1
•	Enforce technical controls that prevent the sending of any email with an "External" recipient if the content is marked with a classification higher than "OFFICIAL".
•	Integrate email security alerts into the centralised SIEM (Splunk) to provide real-time visibility into attempted data breaches or classification overrides.
•	Develop a formal Data Spill Management Plan that includes automated "Search and Purge" scripts to rapidly contain and remediate any classified data that is incorrectly shared via email.
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented.
The implementation of automated classification and strict DLP blocking significantly reduces the probability of a data spill occurring through negligence or technical oversight. By ensuring that sensitive information is technically constrained and that users are prompted to apply correct labels, the likelihood of a major exposure event is reduced to "Unlikely". While the potential consequence of a spill remains "Major" due to the sensitivity of government data, the overall risk is brought within the agency's tolerance levels.
